---
import SiteShell from '../layouts/SiteShell.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from '../consts';
---

<SiteShell title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION}>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">Software &amp; AI Engineering</span>
      <h1>Software as Language.<br />Built for Human Flourishing.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Kecker is a software and AI company that applies classical reasoning to modern engineering.
        Platonic ideals, Aristotelian logos, Stoic virtue — not as ornament, but as method.
        We build systems that are clear, purposeful, and genuinely good.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href="mailto:frontdoor@kecker.co" class="button button-primary">Get in Touch</a>
        <a href="/privacy" class="text-link">Our Privacy Policy →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Philosophy Pillars -->
  <section class="pillars">
    <div class="pillars-inner">
      <div class="pillars-header">
        <span class="eyebrow">Our Philosophy</span>
        <h2>Three traditions. One discipline.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="pillars-grid">
        <article class="pillar-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Platonic Form</span>
          <h3>The Ideal is the Standard</h3>
          <p>
            We pursue the ideal. Every interface, API, and system aims toward the Form of what
            software ought to be: clear, true, and good. The gap between the current and the ideal
            is not a defect to paper over — it is the space in which real craft operates.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="pillar-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Aristotelian Logos</span>
          <h3>Reason as Method</h3>
          <p>
            Reason is our method. We engineer with purpose — understanding the <em>telos</em> of
            every system before writing a line of code. Software without telos is machinery.
            Software with it becomes an instrument of human ends.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="pillar-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Stoic Virtue</span>
          <h3>Excellence as Foundation</h3>
          <p>
            Excellence is the only standard. Like the Stoics, we believe virtue — in code as in
            life — is its own reward and the foundation of lasting work. Shortcuts compound into
            entropy. Rigorous craft compounds into endurance.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What We Build -->
  <section class="services">
    <div class="services-inner">
      <div class="services-header">
        <span class="eyebrow">What We Build</span>
        <h2>Engineering at the intersection of reason and craft.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="services-grid">
        <article class="service-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Mobile &amp; Web</span>
          <h3>Mobile &amp; Web Engineering</h3>
          <p>
            High-performance applications built with the rigor of logos and the craft of virtue.
            We build for the long run — architectures that remain coherent under growth, interfaces
            that stay honest under pressure. We build what endures.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="service-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Artificial Intelligence</span>
          <h3>AI Systems</h3>
          <p>
            Intelligent systems that augment human capacity — designed with semiotic awareness so
            they communicate meaning, not just data. AI that serves the human ends for which it
            was built, rather than optimizing away from them.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="service-card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Semiotics</span>
          <h3>Semiotic UX Design</h3>
          <p>
            Interfaces are sign systems. We design experiences that speak clearly to every user —
            grounded in Peircean semiotics and human-centered reasoning. Meaning is not incidental
            to design; it is the point of it.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Human Flourishing -->
  <section class="flourishing">
    <div class="flourishing-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">On Human Flourishing</span>
      <blockquote class="pull-quote">
        "Software that serves eudaimonia — flourishing for clients, users, employees, and society."
      </blockquote>
      <div class="flourishing-body">
        <p>
          Aristotle called the highest human good <em>eudaimonia</em> — flourishing, not merely
          pleasure or success. We take this seriously as a design constraint. Software that degrades
          attention, exploits users, or externalizes harm onto society is, by definition, bad
          software, regardless of its metrics.
        </p>
        <p>
          The obligation runs in every direction: toward clients who need results they can stand
          behind, toward users who deserve systems that respect their agency, toward employees who
          do their best work when the work is worth doing, and toward the broader social fabric
          that technology inevitably shapes. None of these are in fundamental conflict. Good
          engineering serves all of them.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="cta-section">
    <div class="cta-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">Start a Conversation</span>
      <h2>Ready to build something enduring?</h2>
      <a href="mailto:frontdoor@kecker.co" class="cta-email">frontdoor@kecker.co</a>
    </div>
  </section>

</SiteShell>
